16:38.960 --> 16:40.320
They should get killed for it.

16:41.100 --> 16:41.620
We're right.

16:41.800 --> 16:43.440
But the enlisted men want to stay alive.

16:44.100 --> 16:48.480
As the Osirians said in catch 22, they're trying to kill me.

16:48.880 --> 16:49.580
He didn't mean the enemy.

16:49.680 --> 16:50.800
He meant the army he was in.

16:51.660 --> 16:54.440
And knowing all this, reading all this, catch 22 came out.

16:54.520 --> 16:56.260
I was a great fan of Kandy.

16:57.060 --> 17:00.780
And when I saw catch 22, what he did, the Heller did,

17:01.420 --> 17:08.020
he showed that there's some things so awful that you have to laugh at them to understand them.

17:08.540 --> 17:11.780
If you do a military novel, you say, blood, blood, death, and testines in the trees.

17:11.780 --> 17:15.460
By the 20th time you hang the testines from the trees, you're tired looking at them.

17:15.500 --> 17:16.760
It looks like spaghetti after a while.

17:17.660 --> 17:19.220
Repetition of horror doesn't make horror.

17:19.780 --> 17:20.500
And that's all you can do.

17:20.580 --> 17:23.120
The army is utterly horrible, boring and wasteful.

17:23.260 --> 17:24.920
The military life is boring and wasteful.

17:27.780 --> 17:31.760
And in there, I parodied a few other novels just for fun of it.

17:32.080 --> 17:37.080
But the thing that goes right through it is understanding the military.

17:38.660 --> 17:42.780
Usually I discovered that I had a Korean war veteran come up to me,

17:42.840 --> 17:45.780
he's a combat marine, wouldn't have his face all shut away.

17:47.000 --> 17:48.600
And he said, you're a Korean horse.

17:48.800 --> 17:49.500
I said, yes, yes.

17:50.120 --> 17:51.860
He said, you wrote Bill the Glanting Hero?

17:52.000 --> 17:53.820
I said, yes, looking for a chair to hide behind.

17:54.480 --> 17:57.380
He said, I've got a copy of every edition of that book.

17:57.720 --> 17:59.540
I carry it through to combat, you know.

18:00.000 --> 18:01.520
And that tells a story.

18:02.320 --> 18:05.600
Another guy was the same thing, John Paul.

18:05.600 --> 18:08.960
He was a real Green Beret, the kind that had a bangle.

18:09.100 --> 18:11.460
He worked with the Montagnards, not like John Wayne with the fake one.

18:11.540 --> 18:14.500
He was up there and he killed him, a great killing.

18:18.080 --> 18:21.080
And Napoleon's troops carried a marshals baton in their pack.

18:21.240 --> 18:23.820
He carried a copy of Bill the Glanting Hero, all through the Korean War up there.

18:24.720 --> 18:25.660
Killing gooks and everything.

18:26.520 --> 18:28.600
And he used to get his rookies in.

18:28.960 --> 18:31.940
He read him a chapter every night whether they liked it or not.

18:32.280 --> 18:33.580
He'd break them in half, you know.

18:33.580 --> 18:38.700
And then, so, I really feel that it's humor and parody and a lot of fun.

18:38.960 --> 18:43.440
But it tells you something about the military condition that is absolutely dead true.

18:44.280 --> 18:50.260
It's funny, my next question is, Bill the Glanting Hero is a slap at making war in the military.

18:51.480 --> 18:52.840
Is this what you feel?

