had to change it to Fanny Hill.

20:30.940 --> 20:34.120
So much for, so did the publishers.

20:36.800 --> 20:37.280
Okay.

20:38.220 --> 20:42.520
Make room, make room, which is probably your serious novel,

20:42.800 --> 20:44.480
the one that you're known for, that sort of thing.

20:44.480 --> 20:47.360
And the topic was overpopulation.

20:47.980 --> 20:51.500
And you obviously, when I read it, you obviously felt very strong about population

20:51.500 --> 20:52.880
and yet you didn't preach.

20:53.900 --> 20:55.920
How did you walk that thing line?

20:56.140 --> 20:57.540
And you must feel.

20:57.660 --> 20:58.080
Okay.

20:58.180 --> 21:02.380
Science fiction tends to preach and tell you things, you know.

21:02.700 --> 21:04.740
It goes back to the old pups when you wanted to say,

21:05.060 --> 21:08.320
you should tell them what you're going to tell them, tell them and tell them you told them.

21:08.860 --> 21:12.700
And all the early science fiction, they go into time machine

21:12.700 --> 21:16.660
and there'll be the young assistant or a young girl, young guy, and he said,

21:17.000 --> 21:18.980
tell me professor, how does it work?

21:19.560 --> 21:22.060
Two and a half pages later, you learn how it works, you know.

21:22.600 --> 21:25.500
Which I put the boot in the technical time machine.

21:26.000 --> 21:27.440
I have the same thing happen.

21:28.500 --> 21:32.040
And the guy says, gee, professor, how does the time machine work?

21:32.720 --> 21:35.120
And the professor says, you're too stupid to understand.

21:35.480 --> 21:37.080
And I thought, a good explanation, you know.

21:39.340 --> 21:43.320
Science fiction has a auditory finger, tells you what to do and how to do it.

21:43.680 --> 21:45.080
And I felt very serious about population.

21:45.420 --> 21:48.860
At that time, I wrote the book, there were no fictional works on population.

21:49.200 --> 21:51.680
There were no, these popular nonfiction books hadn't come out.

21:52.040 --> 21:53.740
The world was completely unaware where we were going.

21:54.340 --> 21:55.060
And I could see it.

21:55.080 --> 21:56.420
I lived in Mexico and watched what was happening.

21:56.900 --> 21:58.760
You read the Learned Journalist, he told you about it.

21:59.120 --> 22:03.040
So I wanted to do a propaganda work that was disguised as not being propaganda.

22:04.020 --> 22:07.240
And so I said it in the year 1999 in New York.

22:07.900 --> 22:11.880
It makes a millennial novel, brings a lot of overtones, you know, the millennium,

22:12.140 --> 22:13.440
coming of Christ and the sort of thing.

22:14.320 --> 22:15.980
And I didn't want to lecture.

22:16.700 --> 22:20.020
So I very simply started a book, put the characters in the world,

22:20.080 --> 22:21.940
went along for almost a fifth of the book,

22:23.100 --> 22:28.120
and got everyone involved before someone turned to one character, the older character.

22:28.420 --> 22:30.060
How did the world get this way?

22:30.060 --> 22:34.300
At this point, I felt the reader was trapped enough to take one page of the lecture.

22:34.840 --> 22:36.200
And I sent the book in my hand and said,

22:36.260 --> 22:38.180
Harry, they're trapped up, take four pages of the lecture.

22:38.700 --> 22:42.960
So I just put in four pages, copy about a thousand words, two pages in the book,

22:43.440 --> 22:45.460
telling you how the world got that way.

22:45.500 --> 22:49.380
So my one little lecture right there, having done that little lecture,

22:50.060 --> 22:52.860
so it was in a sense a work of propaganda and art.

22:53.260 --> 22:54.520
If you have better art, better propaganda.

22:55.200 --> 22:56.320
1984 is propaganda.

22:57.360 --> 22:58.400
On the beach is propaganda.

22:58.400 --> 23:00.280
Both art, you get the message.

23:00.740 --> 23:01.340
And that was it.

23:01.520 --> 23:03.520
And after that, I worked around the point.

23:03.640 --> 23:05.220
And if you were alive and warm, you understood it.

23:05.860 --> 23:06.580
And the readers did.

23:09.080 --> 23:09.520
Okay.

23:12.100 --> 23:13.920
Yeah, I have to come in here.

23:14.020 --> 23:18.660
The shortages of materials, water, food, electricity were all made very real by the text.

23:18.800 --> 23:19.660
You weren't lecturing.

23:20.160 --> 23:22.960
It was just obvious and the reader could picture it.

23:22.980 --> 23:27.200
And I thought maybe that might harken back to your artist days about how you visualize things.

23:29.120 --> 23:31.560
As I think, having worked as an artist for a number of years,

23:32.140 --> 23:34.880
I see in my mind when I'm writing, I have a stage of people walking around.

23:35.020 --> 23:36.420
And I see what's in the background, the foreground.

23:36.700 --> 23:38.440
I hear the waves splashing and see them splashing.

23:41.520 --> 23:47.340
And as always in writing, you should never tell you should show.

23:49.360 --> 23:50.840
And good writing is hard work.

23:51.200 --> 23:52.180
It should be transparent.

23:52.920 --> 23:55.080
The reader should not see how you got the effect.

23:55.460 --> 24:00.340
And one of the best ways, of course, it's hard to do is never say the world is full of a lot of people.

24:00.600 --> 24:01.760
Never say you're short of water.

24:01.920 --> 24:05.220
Show them online to get water out of a standpipe.

24:05.540 --> 24:09.080
And then you know you're short of water and dramatize a need for the water.

24:09.940 --> 24:12.080
And this is where your art comes in.

24:14.580 --> 24:19.220
Which, for a lot of people, if the writer cannot do that, then he's not,

24:19.320 --> 24:20.480
that doesn't succeed on that level.

24:20.720 --> 24:22.000
If you read his book for fun, you know,

24:22.000 --> 24:25.800
if you get the reader emotionally involved, get him trapped into the book.

24:26.220 --> 24:29.180
And he comes out again, maybe not agreeing with you,

24:29.340 --> 24:30.520
but at least he knows what you're said.

24:30.620 --> 24:31.640
He'll be thinking about it.

24:32.000 --> 24:34.020
And I had one girl read that book in New York.

24:34.320 --> 24:36.240
She said, if I thought the world would be like that, I commit suicide.

24:36.340 --> 24:37.320
I said, don't, don't.

24:38.060 --> 24:42.700
The actor thinking that means you're going to vote right and work for this world will not appeal.

24:43.160 --> 24:46.780
That's a science fiction admonishing finger again saying, shape up or ship out.

24:47.140 --> 24:48.260
If you don't do this, you'll get that.

24:50.080 --> 24:52.260
I also view this as a detective novel.

24:52.560 --> 24:53.120
Is that fair?

24:54.120 --> 24:54.520
It's fair.

24:55.540 --> 24:59.160
All science fiction, for the most part, is based on detective plot.

24:59.820 --> 25:00.240
It's a mystery.

25:00.420 --> 25:00.980
Will it be solved?

25:01.820 --> 25:05.320
Even if they're not called like Hell, Clemens, Needle, not officially a mystery,

25:05.960 --> 25:07.360
you want to find out how you got that way.

25:07.460 --> 25:08.280
Will they solve the problem?

25:08.420 --> 25:09.120
Will they all live?

25:09.180 --> 25:09.960
Will they get all this world?

25:10.320 --> 25:10.940
Will they do it?

25:11.300 --> 25:15.540
Now that was the deliberate bit of my plot, a plot device of mine

25:15.540 --> 25:19.420
that I wanted to show society from the lowest levels to the high.

25:19.900 --> 25:21.640
I wanted to show how everybody lived in that world.

25:22.100 --> 25:24.660
So I use a very simple device of having a detective as protagonist.

25:25.460 --> 25:26.340
And a very simple story.

25:26.760 --> 25:28.580
And we all know from the beginning who did the murder.

25:28.880 --> 25:30.340
I mean, we knew what's going to happen.

25:30.800 --> 25:34.040
And it was not important, but it was a device to move the story along.

25:34.380 --> 25:37.180
And like most crimes in New York, 9% aren't solved.

25:37.680 --> 25:39.080
It's just by chance that they are.

25:39.480 --> 25:42.320
This is a way of getting you into the various levels of the strategy of society.

